                              "source": [
                                        "from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\n",
                                        "from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression\n",
                                        "from sklearn.linear_model import Ridge, Lasso\n",
                                        "from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n",
                                        "from sklearn.metrics import r2_score, mean_squared_error\n",
                                        "\n",
                                        "# standardize X so that all features are on the same scale before applying Ridge and Lasso\n",
                                        "# without this, features with large values like GrLivArea would dominate the penalty\n",
                                        "X_scaled = StandardScaler().fit_transform(X)\n",
                                        "\n",
                                        "X_train_p4, X_val_p4, y_train_p4, y_val_p4 = train_test_split(\n",
                                        "    X_scaled, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42\n",
                                        ")\n",
                                        "\n",
                                        "results = {}\n",
                                        "\n",
                                        "# OLS : no regularization\n",
                                        "ols_sk = LinearRegression().fit(X_train_p4, y_train_p4)\n",
                                        "results['OLS'] = {\n",
                                        "    'R²':   round(r2_score(y_val_p4, ols_sk.predict(X_val_p4)), 4),\n",
                                        "    'RMSE': round(np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_val_p4, ols_sk.predict(X_val_p4))), 4)\n",
                                        "}\n",
                                        "\n",
                                        "# test Ridge and Lasso with different alpha values (alpha controls the penalty strength)\n",
                                        "for alpha in [0.01, 0.1, 1.0, 10.0]:\n",
                                        "    ridge = Ridge(alpha=alpha).fit(X_train_p4, y_train_p4)\n",
                                        "    lasso = Lasso(alpha=alpha, max_iter=10000).fit(X_train_p4, y_train_p4)\n",
                                        "\n",
                                        "    results[f'Ridge α={alpha}'] = {\n",
                                        "        'R²':   round(r2_score(y_val_p4, ridge.predict(X_val_p4)), 4),\n",
                                        "        'RMSE': round(np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_val_p4, ridge.predict(X_val_p4))), 4)\n",
                                        "    }\n",
                                        "    results[f'Lasso α={alpha}'] = {\n",
                                        "        'R²':   round(r2_score(y_val_p4, lasso.predict(X_val_p4)), 4),\n",
                                        "        'RMSE': round(np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_val_p4, lasso.predict(X_val_p4))), 4)\n",
                                        "    }\n",
                                        "\n",
                                        "# display the results to compare\n",
                                        "display(pd.DataFrame(results).T)"
                              ]
                    },
                    {
                              "cell_type": "markdown",
                              "metadata": {},
                              "source": [
                                        "**Interpretation (20% split):**\n",
                                        "\n",
                                        "We evaluated all models on a held-out validation set (20% of the data)\n",
                                        "that none of the models saw during training.\n",
                                        "\n",
                                        "The two regularized models we tested use the following penalty terms:\n",
                                        "\n",
                                        "**Ridge (L2) :**\n",
                                        "$$\\min \\sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i - \\hat{y}_i)^2 + \\alpha \\sum_{j=1}^{p}\\beta_j^2$$\n",
                                        "\n",
                                        "**Lasso (L1) :**\n",
                                        "$$\\min \\sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i - \\hat{y}_i)^2 + \\alpha \\sum_{j=1}^{p}|\\beta_j|$$\n",
                                        "\n",
                                        "- **Ridge** : R² stays at 0.8424 for all alpha values, same as OLS.\n",
                                        "  Ridge doesn't really change anything here, the regularization has almost no effect.\n",
                                        "- **Lasso** : works fine with small alpha (0.01) but crashes quickly after that.\n",
                                        "  With alpha=1.0 the model predicts nothing (R²≈0.0).\n",
                                        "  This is because Lasso uses |coef| instead of coef², so for a small coefficient like 0.04,\n",
                                        "  Ridge penalizes 0.04²=0.0016 but Lasso penalizes |0.04|=0.04 which is 25x bigger.\n",
                                        "  So Lasso kills the coefficients way faster than Ridge for the same alpha.\n",
                                        "- **Overall OLS is the best model here.**\n",
                                        "\n",
                                        "**Something we noticed :** this time the validation R² (0.8424) is slightly lower\n",
                                        "than the training R² (0.852), which is the expected behavior. The model performs\n",
                                        "a bit better on data it has seen, but the gap is very small which means there is\n",
                                        "almost no overfitting. With only 9 features the model stays simple and generalizes well."
                              ]
                    },
