    "### Interpretation\n",
    "\n",
    "The ANOVA table shows how much each feature contributes to explaining SalePrice once all the others are already in the model.\n",
    "\n",
    "The first thing we notice is that GrLivArea has by far the highest F-statistic (F=624), way ahead of OverallQual (F=212) and CentralAir (F=102). This makes sense because living area is probably the most objective and direct measure of house value — the bigger the house, the more expensive it is, and there is very little noise in that relationship.\n",
    "\n",
    "Something surprising happened with TotalBsmtSF : it is now **not significant** (F=1.28, p=0.259). Before adding the log-transform it was one of the top features, but now the model says it does not really help. We think this is because we log-transformed both GrLivArea and TotalBsmtSF, and they are correlated (big house = big basement). So once GrLivArea is already in the model, TotalBsmtSF does not bring any new information. The model already \"knows\" the size of the house through GrLivArea.\n",
    "\n",
    "We also notice that GrLivArea was not tested in Part 2. That is because ANOVA needs categorical groups and GrLivArea is a continuous variable so we cannot group it directly. We added it manually in Part 4 and it ended up being the most important predictor of all.\n",
